  <item>
    <title>In &amp;#8216;Sunny Side Up,&amp;#8217; artist Eran Shakine pokes fun at lofty notions about art</title>
    <link>http://www.boston.com/ae/books/articles/2012/02/26/in_sunny_side_up_artist_eran_shakine_pokes_fun_at_lofty_notions_about_art</link>
    <description>&lt;p&gt;In &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#8220;Sunny Side Up&amp;#8217;&amp;#8217;&lt;/strong&gt; (Hirmer), artist Eran Shakine, who lives in Tel Aviv and London, pokes fun at lofty notions about art, inspiration, and genius. In the text below his sketch of a museum scene, Shakine notes that museumgoers spend an average of 10 seconds with each work, half of which is spent reading the label. He draws a hairpiece in the shape of, say, a Frank Gehry building and plops it on Gehry&amp;#8217;s head. He dresses Ralph Lauren and other male fashion designers in the clothing they create for women. With a few bold lines, Shakine creates a world of commentary.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    <dc:creator>Jan Gardner</dc:creator>
